(341922,'Coffee Hours',cast('2014-02-12 16:00' as date),cast('2014-02-12 17:00' as date),'205 Lawrence Hall',NULL,NULL,'FC','French club Coffee Hours are social events at which members of Hudson and Hamilton community can practice their French speaking skills, learn about francophone culture, and enjoy snacks that are representative of the French cuisine.',null),
(196131,'Who Cut Off Josephine''s Head: The Politics of Identity and Intangible Cultural Heritage in the Black Atlantic',cast('2012-11-15 19:00' as date),cast('2012-11-15 20:30' as date),'Lawrence Hall, Ho Lecture Room',NULL,NULL,'FC','This event is aimed at introducing aspects of Francophone culture that are often overlooked when studying French, specifically Caribbean history and culture. All students will be invited to hear Professor Curtius speak on the impact of French colonization and culture on Caribbean identity. A symbol of this impact has been the statue of Empress Josephine, wife of Napoleon, which was beheaded in Fort-de-France, Martinique in 1991. She intends to examine the politics of identity and intangible cultural heritage in Martinique, where several Hudson students visited last spring, in hopes to present a different dimension to European and Caribbean identity. Before the lecture, students will have the chance to have personal conversations with Professor Curtius over lunch and promote the use of French conversation outside of the classroom.',null),
(292942,'French Club Coffee Hour',cast('2013-12-04 16:00' as date),cast('2013-12-04 17:00' as date),'French Seminar Room, Lawrence 205',NULL,NULL,'FC',NULL,null),
