(577846,'The Vagina Monolouges',cast('2015-02-14 18:00' as date),cast('2015-02-14 20:30' as date),'Brehmer Theater','Arts',NULL,'SRT','The Vagina Monologues is a show that is performed annually at Hudson. VM was written by playwright and activist Eve Ensler, who crafted the play, sharing a variety of stories of women and their bodies, as well as raise awareness about and to speak back against sexual and domestic violence. The show is performed internationally each year on Valentines day weekend (also know as VDay). Purchase your tickets at the COOP or at the door. All proceeds go to Victims of Violence.',null),
(908749,'Breaking the Silence on Sex Trafficking',cast('2016-02-29 12:15' as date),cast('2016-02-29 13:00' as date),'Chapel Basement','Spirituality',NULL,'UC','Sponsored by University Church in collaboration with the Newman Community, Nicole Braddock Bromley speaks on the topic of stopping sex trafficking.'||chr(10)||'Nicole is the founder of OneVOICE and also the founder and Executive Director of OneVOICE4freedom, a non-profit organization stopping child sex trafficking around the world. In 2012 Nicole was the on-camera talent for a child sex trafficking awareness, rescue and restoration film project of Life Outreach International, where she traveled to Cambodia and met with child sex slaves in brothels and heard their stories. She began OneVOICE4freedom after her return from that life-changing work.',null),
(1142659,'Brothers Welcomes Dr. Vincent T. Harris',cast('2017-02-02 16:30' as date),cast('2017-02-02 18:30' as date),'Love Auditorium','Thoughtful Learning',NULL,'BROS','The Brothers of Hudson University and other sponsors have invited Dr. Vincent T. Harris to talk to faculty and student leaders about how to integrate intentional strategies for the advancement of our male of color undergraduate students, and about how student leaders must create brave spaces through the intersections of race and gender in consecutive discussions in Love Auditorium on Thursday, February 2nd from 4:30 to 6:30 and Friday, February 3rd from 4:30 to 6:00, and 6:30 to 8:00, respectively. The first day will feature a program directed towards faculty and administration, while the second day will address student leaders as well as members of Brothers and other males of color in separate sessions. Dr. Harris aims to educate attendees about ways Hudson University can demonstrate that it is a destination for the advancement of male of color undergraduate students holistic success. After the first discussion with faculty and administrators, we will hold a small reception for Dr. Harris at the President''s House on the night of the 2nd.'||chr(10)||'Dr. Vincent T. Harris serves as Cal State Fullertons inaugural Director of the Male Success Initiative. He manages the comprehensive retention services of increasing access and persistence of men of color, through academic guidance, student leadership development, social engagement, and pre-graduation support for men of color. He is an experienced higher education administrator-scholar whose professional and research track record restores and explores the lived experiences of undergraduate and graduate students as it relates to the intersection of gender, ethnicity, sexual orientation, faith and culture. Most recently, Dr. Harris completed his post-doc employment at Harvard University as an Administrative Fellow in the Harvard College Women''s Center, through the Harvard University Office of Institutional Diversity and Equity.',null),
(1142660,'Brothers Welcomes Dr. Vincent T. Harris',cast('2017-02-03 16:30' as date),cast('2017-02-03 18:00' as date),'Persson Auditorium','Thoughtful Learning',NULL,'BROS','The Brothers of Hudson University and other sponsors have invited Dr. Vincent T. Harris to talk to faculty and student leaders about how to integrate intentional strategies for the advancement of our male of color undergraduate students, and about how student leaders must create brave spaces through the intersections of race and gender in consecutive discussions in Love Auditorium on Thursday, February 2nd from 4:30 to 6:30 and Friday, February 3rd from 4:30 to 6:00, and 6:30 to 8:00, respectively. The first day will feature a program directed towards faculty and administration, while the second day will address student leaders as well as members of Brothers and other males of color in separate sessions. Dr. Harris aims to educate attendees about ways Hudson University can demonstrate that it is a destination for the advancement of male of color undergraduate students holistic success. After the first discussion with faculty and administrators, we will hold a small reception for Dr. Harris at the President''s House on the night of the 2nd.'||chr(10)||'Dr. Vincent T. Harris serves as Cal State Fullertons inaugural Director of the Male Success Initiative. He manages the comprehensive retention services of increasing access and persistence of men of color, through academic guidance, student leadership development, social engagement, and pre-graduation support for men of color. He is an experienced higher education administrator-scholar whose professional and research track record restores and explores the lived experiences of undergraduate and graduate students as it relates to the intersection of gender, ethnicity, sexual orientation, faith and culture. Most recently, Dr. Harris completed his post-doc employment at Harvard University as an Administrative Fellow in the Harvard College Women''s Center, through the Harvard University Office of Institutional Diversity and Equity.',null),
(1142661,'Brothers Welcomes Dr. Vincent T. Harris',cast('2017-02-03 18:30' as date),cast('2017-02-03 20:00' as date),'Love Auditorium','Thoughtful Learning',NULL,'BROS','The Brothers of Hudson University and other sponsors have invited Dr. Vincent T. Harris to talk to faculty and student leaders about how to integrate intentional strategies for the advancement of our male of color undergraduate students, and about how student leaders must create brave spaces through the intersections of race and gender in consecutive discussions in Love Auditorium on Thursday, February 2nd from 4:30 to 6:30 and Friday, February 3rd from 4:30 to 6:00, and 6:30 to 8:00, respectively. The first day will feature a program directed towards faculty and administration, while the second day will address student leaders as well as members of Brothers and other males of color in separate sessions. Dr. Harris aims to educate attendees about ways Hudson University can demonstrate that it is a destination for the advancement of male of color undergraduate students holistic success. After the first discussion with faculty and administrators, we will hold a small reception for Dr. Harris at the President''s House on the night of the 2nd.'||chr(10)||'Dr. Vincent T. Harris serves as Cal State Fullertons inaugural Director of the Male Success Initiative. He manages the comprehensive retention services of increasing access and persistence of men of color, through academic guidance, student leadership development, social engagement, and pre-graduation support for men of color. He is an experienced higher education administrator-scholar whose professional and research track record restores and explores the lived experiences of undergraduate and graduate students as it relates to the intersection of gender, ethnicity, sexual orientation, faith and culture. Most recently, Dr. Harris completed his post-doc employment at Harvard University as an Administrative Fellow in the Harvard College Women''s Center, through the Harvard University Office of Institutional Diversity and Equity.',null),
(1157512,'Danza Caribe',cast('2017-02-25 13:00' as date),cast('2017-02-25 15:00' as date),'Ryan 212','Cultural',NULL,'LASO','As part of the Danza Caribe event we will invite two dance instructors affiliated with one of New Jerseys best and well known dance studios, Chambersburg Dance.'||chr(10)||'A bit about the instructors:'||chr(10)||'Richard Amador, Rich, embraced his love and passion for Salsa and his Puerto Rican heritage as a young boy in his hometown of Allentown, PA.  In college, he pursued his dream of learning how to professionally dance salsa and began training with a well-known dance company in Philadelphia.  Richard then began performing at local venues, banquets, and little did he know his dancing would take him to compete and to even have the chance to perform at the world''s biggest salsa congress in Los Angeles, California!  With a Bachelors of Science in Information Technology, Richard currently works for a small firm as a Technical Analyst in Jersey City, NJ.  He continues to enjoy dancing socially in New Jersey where he currently resides.'||chr(10)||'Zulemy  Rodriguez, Zuly, discovered her love of dance in her hometown of Trenton, NJ where she had the opportunity to train in ballet, tap, jazz, lyrical, acro, hip-hop, and pointe.  She was part of her high school dance team and competed at local and regional competitions.  In college, Zulemy began training with a respected dance company where she received professional instruction in latin dances such as salsa, cha-cha, and bachata.  This opened up performance opportunities in major cities such as Atlantic City, Philadelphia, and Los Angeles.  Zulemy currently holds a Masters of Science and works full-time as a Speech-language Pathologist at a reputable hospital in New Brunswick, NJ.  She continues to share her passion for dance by teaching weekly classes at her home studio with primarily preschool to high school aged students and occasionally, adults.  Zulemy is also part of the dance team staff where she leads exceptional students toward success at local and regional competitions.  Zulemy has collectively 25 years of experience in dance!'||chr(10)||'For the Danza Caribe event, guest instructors will teach dance lessons in segments on Bachata, Merengue, and Salsa which is native to Caribbean countries.',null),
(168901,'Keynote Speaker for Hispanic Heritage Month',cast('2012-10-04 19:00' as date),cast('2012-10-04 20:00' as date),'Love Auditorium',NULL,NULL,'LASO','Sonia Nazario has spent 20 years reporting and writing about social issues, most recently as a'||chr(10)||'projects reporter for The Los Angeles Times. Her stories have tackled some of this countrys most'||chr(10)||'intractable problems: hunger, drug addiction, and immigration.'||chr(10)||'She has won numerous national journalism and book awards. In 2003, her story of a Honduran'||chr(10)||'boys struggle to find his mother in the US, Enriques Journey, won more than a dozen awards, among'||chr(10)||'them the Pulitzer Prize for Feature Writing, the George Polk Award for International Reporting, the'||chr(10)||'Grand Prize of the Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award, and the National Association of Hispanic'||chr(10)||'Journalists Guillermo Martinez-Marquez Award for Overall Excellence.'||chr(10)||'Expanded into a book, Enriques Journey became a national bestseller and won two book'||chr(10)||'awards. It is now required reading for incoming freshmen at dozens of colleges and high schools'||chr(10)||'across the US.'||chr(10)||'In 1998, Nazario was a Pulitzer Prize finalist for a series on children of drug-addicted parents'||chr(10)||'and in 1994, she won a George Polk Award for Local Reporting for a series about hunger among'||chr(10)||'schoolchildren in California.'||chr(10)||'Nazario, who grew up in Kansas and in Argentina, has written extensively from Latin America'||chr(10)||'and about Latinos in the United States. She has been named among the most influential Latinos by'||chr(10)||'Hispanic Business Magazine and a trendsetter by Hispanic Magazine. In 2012, Columbia Journalism'||chr(10)||'Review named her one among 40 women who changed the media business in the past 40 years.'||chr(10)||'She began her career at The Wall Street Journal, where she reported from four bureaus: New'||chr(10)||'York, Atlanta, Miami, and Los Angeles. In 1993, she joined The Los Angeles Times. She is currently at'||chr(10)||'work on her second book.'||chr(10)||'She serves on the advisory boards of the University of North Texas Mayborn Literary Non-fiction'||chr(10)||'Writer''s Conference and of Catch the Next, a nonprofit working to double the number of Latinos'||chr(10)||'enrolling in college.',null),
(1241497,'Midnight Philosophy - Spring 2017 Events',cast('2017-02-11 22:00' as date),cast('2017-04-28 23:00' as date),'COOP/Donovan''s','Thoughtful Learning',NULL,'MPS','Midnight Philosophy Spring 2017 Events and Budget Proposal'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||'Event Schedule'||chr(10)||'02/11/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Skepticism and Science'||chr(10)||'02/18/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Justice and Heroism'||chr(10)||'02/25/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Leadership'||chr(10)||'03/04/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Tribalism and Phobia'||chr(10)||'03/09/17: Midday Philosophy Presents: Religion vs. Secularism in Government'||chr(10)||'03/25/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Justice and Law'||chr(10)||'04/01/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Truth/Knowledge'||chr(10)||'04/08/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Free Will/Determinism'||chr(10)||'04/15/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Purpose and Meaning'||chr(10)||'04/29/17: Midnight Philosophy Presents: Identity and Virtual Reality'||chr(10)||'(Note: topics subject to change.)'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||'Budget Proposal'||chr(10)||'The leaders of Midnight Philosophy estimate the following costs for the events of the Spring 2017 semester:'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||'For six (6) Midnight events at the COOP, we request funding for Slices:'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||''||chr(10)||'2 large cheese pizzas ($24) + 1 large pepperoni pizza ($13) + 2 dozen wings ($14) + 10 sodas ($10) = $61 per event'||chr(10)||'Subtotal = $366'||chr(10)||''||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||'For our one (1) Midday event, we request funding for Hamilton Eatery:'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||''||chr(10)||'Finger sandwich platter ($39) + Penne pasta salad ($5) + Dessert Platter ($18.75) + Drinks ($15) = $77.75 per event'||chr(10)||'Subtotal = $77.75'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||'For our three (3) remaining late-night events at Donovans Pub, we will request late night programming from CLSI. To clarify, Donovans pub often hosts competing weekend events that interfere with our conversations. We request BAC funding because the COOP is a much better environment for debate and understanding.'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||'Sincerely,'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||'Micah Dirkers'||chr(10)||'Class of 2019, Midnight Philosophy President, and'||chr(10)||' '||chr(10)||'Kathryn Chungbin'||chr(10)||'Class of 2018, Midnight Philosophy Vice-President',null);
